<P>
N.Y. FIREBOMB SUSPECT SAYS HE'S A VICTIM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By from Newsday 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Handcuffed to his hospital bed, the man accused as the subway "Mad Bomber" 
said Friday that he's a victim too. 
</P>
<P>
 "I didn't do it," Edward Leary was quoted as saying." . . . I'm not a 'Mad 
Bomber.' How can they say that? They said I did that?" 
</P>
<P>
 Leary said through his lawyer that he was a hapless passenger on the Manhattan 
subway train when a firebomb exploded Wednesday and injured 45 people. 
</P>
<P>
 His attorney, Stephen Murphy, added: "He says he's a victim and is being made 
a victim again." 
</P>
<P>
 Leary, 49, is at New York Hospital-Cornell Burn Center, medicated with 
morphine because of pain caused by the burns he suffered in the explosion. 
Forty percent of his body is covered with third-degree burns, including his 
nose, chin, lips and both legs. 
</P>
<P>
 Leary is charged with 45 counts of first-degree assault. Investigators were 
still taking statements from witnesses and victims on Friday and poring over 
items seized from Leary's home. They are preparing to take the case before a 
Manhattan grand jury by Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Law enforcement sources said the words "Mad Bomber" were scrawled on 
handwritten notes seized from Leary's home in Scotch Plains, N.J., and said 
police found sketches and rambling messages indicating that Leary planned to 
extort money from the Transit Authority by carrying out a series of subway 
bombings. 
