<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY IN BANKRUPTCY; EDITORIAL COMMENTARY ACROSS THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The nation's newspapers have had plenty to say about Orange County's plight.  
</P>
<P>
 With his Navajo jewelry and down-home ways, he was the people's tax collector, 
Robert L. "Bob" Citron. Image mattered: Over 24 years in Orange County, 
California, he rarely let a criticism of his operation go without a blustery 
answer. Now Mr. Citron, who in 1973 became treasurer as well as taxman, is the 
silenced symbol of a colossal overreach in municipal finance. 
</P>
<P>
 WALL STREET JOURNAL, DEC. 9 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Despite all the John Birch Society sound bites, no one among locally elected 
officials (in Orange County) seems to have kept an eye on the former county 
treasurer, Robert Citron . . . His free and easy ways with other people's money 
came to light as a bitter pre-Christmas surprise for 180 of Orange County's 
local government entities whose funds had been entrusted to a single investment 
portfolio managed -- or, rather, mismanaged -- by Citron. 
</P>
<P>
 SAN DIEGO UNION-TRIBUNE, DEC. 13 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 What Orange County needed was oversight. Mr. Citron was seemingly left to run 
amok. Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, calls 
on state and local governments to monitor investment managers of taxpayer money 
. . . If fund managers were forced to assess and report risks, and government 
supervisors were responsible for overseeing the managers, then Orange County -- 
one of the wealthiest in America -- would not now be threatening to lay off 
teachers and nurses. 
</P>
<P>
 NEW YORK TIMES, DEC. 15 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 There will be plenty of time later to lay blame for the investment speculation 
that has now forced Orange County to file for bankruptcy protection. But what's 
critical now is swift leadership from the state to contain the crisis. The 
immediate problem is to shore up Orange County's investment fund and provide 
liquidity for the agencies that have invested, to keep them from tumbling like 
dominoes into bankruptcy themselves. 
</P>
<P>
 SACRAMENTO BEE, DEC. 9 
</P>
</TEXT>
