<P>
RABBI SOLOMON GAON; LEADING SEPHARDI RABBI 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Rabbi Solomon Gaon, 82, chief rabbi of congregations affiliated with the World 
Sephardi Federation. The rabbi was an international spokesman for Sephardic 
Jews -- descendants of those who fled the Spanish Inquisition in 1492 -- and a 
world-renowned scholar on their history and interpretation of Jewish law.Gaon 
was born in Travnik, Bosnia. He began working with Yeshiva University in New 
York in 1962, and in 1968 he was elected president of the American Society of 
Sephardi Studies. The same year Gaon delivered the main address at the 
dedication of the first synagogue consecrated in Spain since King Ferdinand and 
Queen Isabella's expulsion of the Jews in the 15th Century. He received Spain's 
equivalent of the Nobel Prize in 1990 when he was presented with the Prince of 
Austurias Concord Prize. He had been chief rabbi of the congregations 
affiliated with the World Sephardi Federation since 1978. In New York on 
Wednesday of pneumonia. 
