<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: VILLA PARK; FEDERAL DRAINAGE GUIDELINES APPROVED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL BILLITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council, to comply with federal requirements, has approved a sweeping 
ordinance that governs water-runoff drainage. 
</P>
<P>
 Federal law requires all local governments to adopt controls over drainage if 
runoff endangers federally controlled bodies of water, such as the Pacific 
Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
 Villa Park officials have publicly and privately muttered in recent months 
that their small city, with a population of 6,400, hardly has any pollutants 
for the federal government to be worried about. Villa Park is almost entirely 
residential and has no industries. 
</P>
<P>
 Nonetheless, the City Council on Tuesday scrutinized a 23-page model ordinance 
on drainage control and then, without debate, unanimously approved it. No one 
showed up for a public hearing scheduled prior to the vote. BILL BILLITER 
</P>
</TEXT>
