<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: MISSION VIEJO; 2 FAMILIES DREAM UP CHRISTMAS LIGHT SHOW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Almost until midnight, the cars cruise slowly along normally quiet Cervantes 
Lane, the riders gasping at the side-by-side Christmas light shows proudly 
displayed by two neighboring families. 
</P>
<P>
 For about three weeks during the Christmas holiday, life changes for the 
Walkers, the Liesers and their neighbors, but nobody's complaining. 
</P>
<P>
 "You don't have time to do anything else," said Scott Walker, standing outside 
his home greeting strangers who came to gawk appreciatively. "But it's good for 
the community to have a place to go. It helps build community spirit." 
</P>
<P>
 The homes at 25172 and 25162 Cervantes Lane won top awards in the city Home 
Holiday Lighting Contest. For Walker, it was the third time his family has won 
the honor in the five years they've put up the light show. 
</P>
<P>
 Walker's theme is Santa's Fitness Center. His entire front lawn and roof 
covered in cotton snow, the display features animated cartoon reindeer that 
haul up barbells and dutifully drop into sets of deep knee bends. 
</P>
<P>
 Even Santa gets into the act, pumping huge bags of presents attached to an 
iron bar. 
</P>
<P>
 Next door, Michele and Garry Lieser strung together thousands of multicolored 
lights into a religious display featuring wire-framed angels.  
</P>
<P>
 Walker said there is no competition between the two families. The neighbors 
started their displays about five years ago after jointly stringing lights on a 
tree between the two homes. 
</P>
<P>
 It takes Walker, wife Debbie and two helpers about 120 hours to build the 
display, although Walker said the job "gets easier every year because you add 
things to it like building blocks." 
</P>
<P>
 People who gathered in front of the two homes on a pre-Christmas evening this 
week said they appreciated the effort. 
</P>
<P>
 "There's got to be about a trillion lights here," said Lake Forest resident 
Steve Hawkins, who brought his wife and two children. "My kids love this and 
I'm glad these people take the trouble. This is the kind of stuff that puts you 
in the holiday spirit."FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</TEXT>
